# ShepitNote configuration
# Copy this file to .shepitnoterc and edit to your needs.
# This file is sourced as bash, so standard shell syntax applies.

# Directory where recordings are stored
# Default: ./recordings (relative to the shepitnote directory)
#RECORDINGS_DIR="${HOME}/meeting-notes"

# Whisper model size: tiny, base, small, medium, large-v3
# Larger models are more accurate but slower and use more memory.
# large-v3 gives the best multilingual (uk/ru/en) accuracy and reduces
# Ukrainian-vs-Russian confusion, but is ~3GB and runs near real-time on CPU
# (no usable GPU on this target). Override with base/small when speed matters.
# Default: large-v3
#WHISPER_MODEL=large-v3

# Language code for transcription. Recommended: uk, ru, en, or auto.
# Omit, leave empty, or set to "auto" to auto-detect.
# Auto-detect samples only the first ~30s and picks ONE language for the whole
# file; Ukrainian is often mislabeled as Russian. Set this explicitly for a
# known-language meeting (e.g. uk) to avoid that. Any faster-whisper code works.
# See the README "Language selection" section for details.
#WHISPER_LANGUAGE=uk

# --- English tech-term accuracy (issue #8) --------------------------------
# All three settings below are opt-in and empty by default; leaving them unset
# reproduces the pre-#8 behavior exactly. See the README section
# "English tech-term accuracy (hotwords + glossary)" for the full guide.

# WHISPER_HOTWORDS: space-separated product/service/tech terms used to bias
# Whisper decoding toward clean English spellings instead of phonetic Cyrillic
# (e.g. "кубернетес" -> "Kubernetes"). Applied only when WHISPER_INITIAL_PROMPT
# is empty. Keep the list modest — an overly long list can cause hallucinated
# insertions of the seeded terms.
#WHISPER_HOTWORDS="Kubernetes deploy Helm chart Jenkins GitHub Postgres Grafana"

# WHISPER_INITIAL_PROMPT: a natural-sentence decoding bias. Takes precedence over
# WHISPER_HOTWORDS — faster-whisper ignores hotwords when an initial prompt is
# set, so set only one of the two.
#WHISPER_INITIAL_PROMPT="We discuss Kubernetes, deploys, Helm charts, Jenkins, GitHub, Postgres and Grafana."

# GLOSSARY_DIR: directory holding the per-language term glossaries applied to the
# transcript before summarization. Files are: glossary.txt (shared, all
# languages) and glossary.<lang>.txt (e.g. glossary.uk.txt, glossary.ru.txt).
# Ship templates live next to shepitnote as glossary*.txt.example — copy one and
# edit it to activate, e.g.:  cp glossary.uk.txt.example glossary.uk.txt
# Real glossary.*.txt files are git-ignored (they match *.txt), so they stay
# untracked automatically.
# Default: the shepitnote script directory.
#GLOSSARY_DIR="${HOME}/.config/shepitnote"
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------

# --- Participant roster (known names + roles) -----------------------------
# The summarizer otherwise GUESSES who spoke and what their role is, purely from
# the transcript. On multi-party calls that misfires: people who were only
# mentioned get listed as participants, one speaker is split across two names,
# and roles are invented. A roster fixes this by giving the model ground truth.
#
# ROSTER_DIR: directory holding roster.txt. One person per line:
#     Name | role | alias1, alias2, ...
# A leading '*' marks YOU (the local mic / "You" track). Copy the shipped
# roster.txt.example -> roster.txt and edit it. roster.txt is git-ignored (it
# matches *.txt), so real names stay untracked. Default: GLOSSARY_DIR.
#ROSTER_DIR="${HOME}/.config/shepitnote"
#
# MEETING_SELF_NAME / MEETING_SELF_ROLE: your name and role for the local ("You")
# track. An alternative to the '*' line in roster.txt; if both are set these win.
#MEETING_SELF_NAME="Yuriy"
#MEETING_SELF_ROLE="CTO / dev lead"
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Ollama model for summarization
# Default: llama3.1:8b
#OLLAMA_MODEL=llama3.1:8b

# Ollama API URL
# Default: http://localhost:11434
#OLLAMA_URL=http://localhost:11434

# --- Cloud mode (opt-in; OFF by default) -----------------------------------
# Everything runs locally unless you turn cloud mode on for a run with
# `./shepitnote --cloud ...` (or uncomment CLOUD=true to make it the default).
# When on:
#   * summaries run on CLOUD_SUMMARY_MODEL via Ollama Cloud (needs `ollama
#     signin`; no local RAM/CPU cost);
#   * transcription uploads audio to the Whisper API below IF a key is set,
#     otherwise it transparently falls back to local Whisper.
# `--no-cloud` forces local for a run even when CLOUD=true. Cloud sends your
# transcript (and, for cloud transcription, your audio) off this machine.
# See docs/CLOUD.md for the full guide, providers, and privacy notes.
# Default: false
#CLOUD=true

# Ollama Cloud model used for summaries in cloud mode. Default gpt-oss:120b-cloud
# is on Ollama's FREE tier and gave the most accurate Russian-meeting notes in
# testing here; gemma4:31b-cloud is a lighter free alternative. The strongest
# multilingual (ru/uk) models — qwen3.5:cloud, glm-5.2:cloud — need a paid Ollama
# Pro plan. Default: gpt-oss:120b-cloud
#CLOUD_SUMMARY_MODEL=gpt-oss:120b-cloud

# Cloud transcription provider. ANY OpenAI-compatible /audio/transcriptions
# endpoint works — Groq (preset below), Fireworks, Together, OpenAI — by setting
# just these three. Groq's free tier covers ~8h of audio/day and is the fastest.
# Default base URL / model: Groq, whisper-large-v3.
#CLOUD_TRANSCRIBE_BASE_URL=https://api.groq.com/openai/v1
#CLOUD_TRANSCRIBE_MODEL=whisper-large-v3

# API key for cloud transcription. GROQ_API_KEY is accepted as an alias. Get a
# free Groq key at console.groq.com. Until this is set, transcription stays local
# even in cloud mode (so the summary can be cloud while audio never leaves).
#GROQ_API_KEY=gsk_...
#CLOUD_TRANSCRIBE_API_KEY=...

# Use cloud summaries but keep transcription local (audio never leaves): set
# CLOUD=true and CLOUD_TRANSCRIBE=false. An explicit value here always wins over
# the master switch. Default: follows CLOUD.
#CLOUD_TRANSCRIBE=false
#
# The mirror image — cloud transcription (fast) but a LOCAL summary (many find
# the local model writes nicer notes): set CLOUD=true and CLOUD_SUMMARIZE=false,
# or pass --local-summary for a single run. The transcript's audio is uploaded
# for transcription, but summarizing stays on your local Ollama model.
# An explicit value always wins over the master switch. Default: follows CLOUD.
#CLOUD_SUMMARIZE=false
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Audio recording backend: ffmpeg or pw-record
# Use pw-record for Bluetooth headsets (HSP/HFP mode via PipeWire).
# Default: ffmpeg
#RECORD_BACKEND=ffmpeg

# Audio source type: microphone, monitor, both, or dual
#   microphone — microphone input only (default; any unrecognized value also
#                falls back to the default source)
#   monitor    — system audio (sink monitor) only, captures what plays through
#                speakers
#   both       — mix mic and sink monitor into one track (useful for recording
#                calls; the mixed fallback)
#   dual       — record two synchronized tracks: microphone -> voice (You) and
#                sink monitor -> system (Remote). The transcript is labeled by
#                track of origin (You vs Remote) without diarization.
# dual honors RECORD_BACKEND (ffmpeg or pw-record) just like the other modes.
# Default: microphone
#AUDIO_SOURCE_TYPE=microphone

# --- Split the Remote track into per-speaker labels (issue #11) ------------
# In dual mode the far side normally shares one [Remote] label. Set this to
# true to diarize the *system track only* so several people on the call become
# [Remote 1] / [Remote 2] / ... The microphone track is never diarized, so
# [You] stays clean regardless.
#
# Opt-in and best-effort: it needs HF_TOKEN (see below) and pyannote installed
# (pip install pyannote.audio). If either is missing, or diarization fails, the
# meeting still completes with a single [Remote] label. A lone detected speaker
# keeps the plain [Remote] (numbering only appears when 2+ are found).
# Default: false
#DUAL_REMOTE_DIARIZATION=true
#
# Optional hint for the far-side speaker count (helps pyannote when you know it).
# Leave unset to auto-detect. DUAL_REMOTE_MIN_SPEAKERS / DUAL_REMOTE_MAX_SPEAKERS
# bound the estimate instead of fixing it.
#DUAL_REMOTE_SPEAKERS=3
#DUAL_REMOTE_MIN_SPEAKERS=2
#DUAL_REMOTE_MAX_SPEAKERS=5

# Unload Ollama models before transcription to free VRAM for Whisper.
# Set to 1 if you run into out-of-memory errors during transcription.
# Default: unset (disabled)
#UNLOAD_OLLAMA=1

# --- CPU usage limits (keep the desktop responsive during processing) --------
# Post-meeting work (faster-whisper transcription, pyannote diarization, Ollama
# summarization) is CPU-heavy on a machine without a usable GPU. These two knobs
# stop it from taking the whole system hostage; you can watch the effect in
# `htop` / `btop` while a meeting processes.
#
# CPU_THREADS caps the worker thread pools (faster-whisper, pyannote via
# OMP_NUM_THREADS, and Ollama via num_thread) so cores stay free for your
# browser/editor. Default: half the logical CPUs (minimum 1). Set to 0 to leave
# everything uncapped (each library's own default). Raise it for faster
# processing, lower it to keep more cores free.
#CPU_THREADS=12
#
# PROCESSING_NICE lowers the scheduling priority (0..19) of the CPU-heavy workers
# so interactive apps always preempt them — this is what keeps the machine from
# feeling frozen even at full CPU. Default: 10. Higher = yields more (19 = only
# runs on otherwise-idle cores); 0 disables the nice wrapper.
#PROCESSING_NICE=10

# Maximum seconds for the process/process-last commands before timing out.
# Default: 7200 (2 hours)
#PROCESS_TIMEOUT=7200

# Silence detection threshold in dB for tail trimming.
# More negative = stricter (only very quiet audio counts as silence).
# Default: -35
#TRIM_NOISE_DB=-35

# Minimum continuous silence duration in seconds to consider a tail silent.
# Default: 60
#TRIM_MIN_SILENCE=60

# Post-summary hook: path to an executable that runs after every summary is created.
# Receives the summary file path as $1.
# On success, shepitnote writes a .hook_done marker so the hook is not re-run.
# Use this to integrate with Outline, Notion, a webhook, or any other destination.
#
# Example using the bundled shepitnote-to-outline script:
#POST_SUMMARY_HOOK="${HOME}/.local/bin/shepitnote-to-outline"
#
# Example using the bundled Confluence publisher (issue #3, see the CONFLUENCE_*
# block below and the README "Confluence publishing" section):
#POST_SUMMARY_HOOK="${HOME}/path/to/shepitnote/hooks/confluence_publish.py"
#
# Example publishing to BOTH Confluence (full notes) and Slack (short TL;DR):
# point the hook at the bundled dispatcher, which runs each publisher that is
# configured (Confluence first, so its page link is available to the Slack
# message). See the SLACK_* block below and the README "Slack publishing" and
# "Publishing to both" sections.
#POST_SUMMARY_HOOK="${HOME}/path/to/shepitnote/hooks/publish.py"

# --- Confluence publishing (issue #3) -------------------------------------
# Used only by hooks/confluence_publish.py (set POST_SUMMARY_HOOK above to it).
# The hook converts each summary to Confluence storage format and creates — or,
# on re-run, updates — a page titled "<meeting title> - YYYY-MM-DD" (or
# "Meeting HH:MM - YYYY-MM-DD" when the recording had no title) in the target
# space. Re-running the same meeting updates the same page, never duplicates.
#
# NOTE: the hook publishes whenever it is invoked. Confirm-gating before publish
# arrives with the terminal UI (issue #5); for now enabling it is opt-in purely
# by setting POST_SUMMARY_HOOK. Preview output first with the dry-run below.
#
# Preview without any credentials (prints the storage XHTML, no API call):
#   hooks/confluence_publish.py recordings/<date>/meeting_<ts>/meeting_<ts>_summary.md --dry-run
#
# Required for a real publish:
# CONFLUENCE_BASE_URL: your wiki base, NO trailing /rest/api.
#   Cloud:      https://yourorg.atlassian.net/wiki
#   Server/DC:  https://confluence.yourorg.com
#CONFLUENCE_BASE_URL="https://yourorg.atlassian.net/wiki"
#
# CONFLUENCE_SPACE_KEY: the target space key (e.g. ENG, TEAM, ~yourname).
#CONFLUENCE_SPACE_KEY="ENG"
#
# CONFLUENCE_API_TOKEN: Cloud API token OR Server/DC Personal Access Token.
#   Cloud token:  https://id.atlassian.com/manage-profile/security/api-tokens
#   Server/DC PAT: your profile -> Personal Access Tokens
# Never commit a real token; keep it in your private .shepitnoterc only.
#CONFLUENCE_API_TOKEN="your-api-token"
#
# Optional:
# CONFLUENCE_EMAIL: your Atlassian account email. Its presence selects Cloud
#   HTTP Basic (email:token); leave it unset for Server/DC Bearer (PAT) auth.
#CONFLUENCE_EMAIL="you@yourorg.com"
#
# CONFLUENCE_PARENT_PAGE_ID: numeric id of a parent page. When set, new pages are
#   created under it and updates re-assert it as the parent.
#CONFLUENCE_PARENT_PAGE_ID="123456"
#
# CONFLUENCE_AUTH_MODE: force the auth scheme, "basic" or "bearer". When unset it
#   is derived from CONFLUENCE_EMAIL (set -> basic, unset -> bearer).
#CONFLUENCE_AUTH_MODE="basic"
#
# CONFLUENCE_DRY_RUN: set to 1 to force dry-run (same as the --dry-run flag) — the
#   hook prints the storage XHTML and never calls the API.
#CONFLUENCE_DRY_RUN=1
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------

# --- Slack publishing (issue #4) ------------------------------------------
# Used by hooks/slack_publish.py (run it directly, or via hooks/publish.py to
# publish to Slack AND Confluence in one hook). It runs a SECOND, terser Ollama
# pass over the summary — a 3-5 bullet TL;DR plus action items, distinct from the
# full notes — renders it as Slack mrkdwn, appends a link to the Confluence page
# when one exists (from the <base>.confluence_page_id marker written by #3 +
# CONFLUENCE_BASE_URL above), and posts it. The TL;DR pass reuses OLLAMA_MODEL /
# OLLAMA_URL from above (falling back to the same llama3.1:8b / localhost:11434
# defaults). See the README "Slack publishing" section for the full guide.
#
# Slack posts are NOT idempotent, so on a confirmed post the hook writes a
# sibling <base>.slack_done marker and never re-posts for that meeting — retries
# are safe (at most one message per meeting).
#
# NOTE: the hook posts whenever it is invoked. Confirm-gating before posting
# arrives with the terminal UI (issue #5); for now enabling it is opt-in purely
# by setting POST_SUMMARY_HOOK. Preview output first with the dry-run below.
#
# Preview without any token/webhook (prints the TL;DR + target + payload, no post;
# still calls the local Ollama to build the TL;DR):
#   hooks/slack_publish.py recordings/<date>/meeting_<ts>/meeting_<ts>_summary.md --dry-run
#
# Pick ONE of the two auth/target styles:
#
# (A) Incoming webhook — the channel is baked into the webhook URL. Create one at
#   https://api.slack.com/messaging/webhooks
#   Keep it private; the webhook URL is a credential and is never printed.
#SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL="https://hooks.slack.com/services/XXX/YYY/ZZZ"
#
# (B) Bot token — post via chat.postMessage to an explicit channel. Create a bot,
#   give it chat:write, install it to the workspace, invite it to the channel.
#SLACK_BOT_TOKEN="xoxb-your-bot-token"
#SLACK_CHANNEL="#meetings"
#
# Optional:
# SLACK_AUTH_MODE: force "webhook" or "bot". When unset it is derived from which
#   of the above is set (both set -> webhook wins).
#SLACK_AUTH_MODE="webhook"
#
# SLACK_DRY_RUN: set to 1 to force dry-run (same as the --dry-run flag).
#SLACK_DRY_RUN=1
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Notification command override. By default shepitnote uses dunstify (if available)
# with replace-by-ID so reminders update in place, falling back to notify-send.
# Set this to use a different notifier, e.g. mako, fnott, or a custom script.
# Will be called as: $NOTIFY_CMD "summary" "body"
#NOTIFY_CMD=notify-send

# HuggingFace API token — required for speaker diarization (pyannote models),
# including DUAL_REMOTE_DIARIZATION above.
# Create a token at https://huggingface.co/settings/tokens
# Accept model conditions at https://huggingface.co/pyannote/speaker-diarization-community-1
# (pyannote.audio 4.x; the model is downloaded and cached locally on first use).
#HF_TOKEN=hf_...
